Demographers report that divorce rates are much lower in Senegal than in Europe, as marriage is considered a sacred rite (cemti), strictly protected by the law against outside intervention.

Unfortunately, discontinuing a marriage is a lengthy process in Senegal. It involves completing divorce certificate requests, obtaining copies of marriage documents from the state and the religious courts (mariage est légal deux documents: demande de divorce’’ (‘‘Les responsables du domicile’’).), and submitting them to the appropriate parties in Senegal. The legal procedures vary according to the jurisdiction and religious background of the couple. In the 75 districts where Williche is spoken, the procedure is the same regardless of religion: a hearing must be organized, after the negotiations between the Apostolic and the Villiche are completed. Photocopies of the marriage contract and birth certificate are sent to the court. The couple appears before a judge, who examines the original marriage contract and hears testimony from the informant. He rules on whether the couple is still husband and wife. If he decides otherwise, the judge will sign the divorce certificate.
